This is an example of how you might use the Plush Advanced Prompt Enhancer and Tagger nodes
to construct an Agentic Cascade (A chain of AI models each assigned specific roles as
"Agents" that sequentially process information in order to produce enhanced output).
In this example there are three AI agents: Draft Writer, Evaluator and Final Composer.
This agentic Cascade is designed to produce final output that adheres closer to the
original instructions than the draft output: (Instruction Adherence).
You may or may not agree that the final output here is an improvement, but this workflow
only serves as an example of how you might structure an agentic Cascade using these tools.
How well it works will depend on well you instruct your models.
In this case a Draft Writer agent receives an Instruction [System] and a prompt [User] and
produces output based on this input. The Evaluator receives its Instruction [System] and
the Draft Writer's Instruction + Draft Writer's output [User] and produces corrections as
its output. Finally the Final Composer receives its instructions [System] and the Draft
Writer's output + the Evaluator's corrections [User] and produces a corrected final
I've included the yellow "View" nodes on top so you can see the intermediate information
passed between each agent node. These are just informational and aren't necessary for the
workflow to function. I've also included nodes titled "Separator", these are just
collapsed Tagger nodes that insert new lines and asterisks to make reading the intermediate
output easier. Whether this separator makes the text more understandable to the AI depends
= Label combined input. You might label the tagger combined input to make it clearer to
the AI. For instance in the "Draft Instructions & Draft Prompt" Tagger node you might add
additional Tagger nodes to preface the two input items with "Draft Instruction:" and "Draft
Prompt" to make it clear to the AI which part of the input text is which. Whether this is
necessary will depend on how well your AI can interpret the input.
= Reiterate the Instructions: You may find your model performs better if you reiterate the
agent's instructions at the end of the prompt input. For instance you may want to send the
Evaluator agent the Draft Writer's Instructions + the Draft Prompt + a brief summary of the
Evaluator's instruction as a separate paragraph at the end. Some AI models perform better
if you reinforce its instructions near the end of the text by repeating it in brief so that
what it's supposed to do doesn't get lost in the other lengthy text input.
= Refine the Instructions: Experiment with the Instructions given to each agent and tailor
them to fit the interpretive strengths and weaknesses of the model.
= Change the creative_latitude: In my example all the agents have the same creative
latitude. But you may find that the Draft Writer needs more creative latitude and the
Evaluator less. It depends on the models.
= Use different models for each agent. You many want to incorporate local models based on
your familiarity with them, or if you think they're better suited to the task. One benefit
of a well designed agentic Cascade is that often smaller/local models can be use to create
output that's just as good as large frontier models.

In this example there are three AI agents: Draft Writer, Evaluator and Final Composer. This agentic Cascade is designed to produce final output that adheres closer to the original instructions than the draft output: (Instruction Adherence). 

You may or may not agree that the final output here is an improvement, but this workflow only serves as an example of how you might structure an agentic Cascade using these tools. How well it works will depend on well you instruct your models.
 
In this case a Draft Writer agent receives an Instruction [System] and a prompt [User] and produces output based on this input. The Evaluator receives its Instruction [System] and the Draft Writer's Instruction + Draft Writer's output [User] and produces corrections as its output. Finally the Final Composer receives its instructions [System] and the Draft Writer's output + the Evaluator's corrections [User] and produces a corrected final composition as output.

I've included the yellow "View" nodes on top so you can see the intermediate information passed between each agent node. These are just informational and aren't necessary for the workflow to function. I've also included nodes titled "Separator", these are just collapsed Tagger nodes that insert new lines and asterisks to make reading the intermediate output easier. Whether this separator makes the text more understandable to the AI depends on the model. 

Things you might consider:

= Label combined input. You might label the tagger combined input to make it clearer to the AI. For instance in the "Draft Instructions & Draft Prompt" Tagger node you might add additional Tagger nodes to preface the two input items with "Draft Instruction:" and "Draft Prompt" to make it clear to the AI which part of the input text is which. Whether this is necessary will depend on how well your AI can interpret the input.

= Reiterate the Instructions: You may find your model performs better if you reiterate the agent's instructions at the end of the prompt input. For instance you may want to send the Evaluator agent the Draft Writer's Instructions + the Draft Prompt + a brief summary of the Evaluator's instruction as a separate paragraph at the end. Some AI models perform better if you reinforce its instructions near the end of the text by repeating it in brief so that what it's supposed to do doesn't get lost in the other lengthy text input.

= Refine the Instructions: Experiment with the Instructions given to each agent and tailor them to fit the interpretive strengths and weaknesses of the model.

= Change the creative_latitude: In my example all the agents have the same creative latitude. But you may find that the Draft Writer needs more creative latitude and the Evaluator less. It depends on the models.

= Use different models for each agent. You many want to incorporate local models based on your familiarity with them, or if you think they're better suited to the task. One benefit of a well designed agentic Cascade is that often smaller/local models can be use to create output that's just as good as large frontier models.
